sec.p:
Superficially, the two species appear to belong in the genus Diaphonia , but they do not exhibit all the characters of this genus ( Hutchinson & Moeseneder 2013 , 2019;
Moeseneder et al . 2019
). Hence, we here describe Rigoutorum new genus for D. bacchusi , resulting in Rigoutorum bacchusi new combination , and Rigoutorum jakli new species for the second taxon.

Sequence trace files were assembled, PCR primers were trimmed, and consensus sequences aligned using Geneious 10.2.6 (
Kearse et al. 2012
). Trace files, consensus sequences and specimen data were uploaded to BOLD ( Ratnasingham & Hebert 2007 ) (http://boldsystems.org) and are available as public dataset DS-RIGOUT (https:// doi.org/10.5883/DS-RIGOUT). Sequences were also submitted to GenBank.

Phylogenetic analyses used the same partitioning scheme and model as in
Mitchell et al. (2020)
for their larger COI dataset for Australian Cetoniinae, i.e. , a single data partition and the general time reversible model with gamma-distributed rates and invariable sites (GTR+G+I). Phylogenetic analyses were performed by Bayesian inference (BI) using MrBayes version 3.2.6 (
Ronquist et al. 2012
) and under maximum likelihood (ML) using RAxML version 8.2.10 ( Stamatakis 2014 ), using the Geneious plugins available. The BI analysis was set to run for 1 million generations, with a sample frequency of 1,000, using 2 runs, setting the number of chains to 4. The average standard deviation of split frequencies dropped below 0.01, indicating convergence of the chains. The burnin fraction was set to 0.25. ML analysis used the hill-climbing algorithm with 1,000 rapid bootstrap replicates.

The new COI data presented here (
) support morphological observations that Diaphonia is not a monophyletic group and should be restricted to those taxa closely allied to the type species, D. dispar . While it is clear that two species should be split off to create a new genus, Rigoutorum , the details of relationships among other Diaphonia species
, Aphanesthes and HemichnoodesKraatz, 1880 will require further data to resolve, especially nuclear gene data.

