Distribution. Mapping the collecting locations of Rigoutorum species
(
) provided further evidence of the existence of two species in this genus. Their ranges are geographically separated by a gap of approximately 50 km and orientated in northwest-southeast direction in southern Western Australia . Diaphonia bacchusi occurs as the southeastern species; its holotype is from Southern Cross. The paratype of Diaphonia bacchusi , from Marloo Station near Wurarga, is representative of the northwestern population and is described as Rigoutorum jakli . Annual average rainfall (
) and climate (
) data were added to the spatial distribution. Based on these results, R. jakli appear to generally inhabit hot semi-arid and desert regions with an annual average temperature of over 18 °C (Köppen-Geiger classes BWh and BSh) (
). Rigoutorum bacchusi occur generally in cold semi-arid and desert regions with annual average temperatures of less than 18 °C (Köppen-Geiger classes BSk and BWk) (
).

